    <summaries>
      <summary>
        <versionCode>00</versionCode>
        <actionDate>2021-05-20</actionDate>
        <actionDesc>Introduced in Senate</actionDesc>
        <updateDate>2022-02-28T13:01:02Z</updateDate>
        <text>
          <![CDATA[ <p><b>Diversifying by Investing in Educators and Students To Improve Outcomes For Youth Act or the Diversify Act</b></p> <p>This bill revises the Teacher Education Assistance for College and Higher Education (TEACH) grant program. The TEACH program awards grants to undergraduate and graduate students who commit to teaching in a high-need field and in an elementary or secondary school that serves low-income students. </p> <p>First, the bill raises the maximum amount for TEACH grants.</p> <p>Second, the bill allows TEACH grants to cover the full cost of attendance. Currently, these grants may be used only for tuition, fees, and on-campus housing. </p> <p>The bill allows teaching in a high-need early childhood education program to count toward service requirements for the program.</p> <p>Next, the bill eliminates the process for converting a TEACH grant to a loan if a recipient does not complete the requirements of the program. Further, the bill prohibits the Department of Education (ED) from instituting or creating a monetary penalty for failure or refusal to complete the service requirement.</p> <p>In addition, the bill requires ED to send an electronic certificate to grant recipients who have completed their service requirement.</p> <p>The bill also exempts the TEACH program from sequestration, which is a process of automatic, usually across-the-board spending reductions under which budgetary resources are permanently cancelled to enforce specific budget policy goals. </p>]]>
        </text>
      </summary>
